    <section id="living-with" class="content-section">
      <h2>Living with FIV</h2>
      <p>FIV-positive cats can live long, full lives. The diagnosis changes some things — monitoring frequency, vaccination choices, the calculus around medications that suppress the immune system — but it does not determine a cat's quality of life or how much time they have. Artie had FIV alongside FIV, hyperthyroidism, and asthma, and then neurological symptoms. Sorbet is currently FIV positive and well-managed. In both cases, the FIV diagnosis was not what drove the difficulty. The other conditions were harder to manage.</p>
      <p>FeLV is a different virus with a more significant impact — but even FeLV-positive cats can have years of good quality life with attentive care. The most important thing with either diagnosis is accurate information about what it actually means, and advocacy against any recommendations that treat the diagnosis itself as a reason to limit care.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>FIV is not a reason to euthanise a cat.</strong> A positive test sometimes leads to this recommendation — at shelters, or occasionally from vets. It should not. An FIV-positive cat with no other health problems has every reason to have years of good life ahead.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="advocacy" class="content-section">
      <h2>What good advocacy looks like</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li><strong>Confirm the diagnosis was properly done.</strong> The initial ELISA screen that detects FIV can produce false positives, especially in kittens who may have maternal antibodies. Ask whether the result has been confirmed with a more specific test, particularly if the result is unexpected.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask how the FIV affects treatment decisions for any other condition.</strong> Some medications routinely used for other conditions carry additional risks in immunocompromised cats. Name both the FIV and the other condition, and ask specifically about interactions.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask which vaccines should be avoided.</strong> Live vaccines can cause problems in immunocompromised cats. Your vet should be aware of this — but make sure it's part of the conversation.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask what monitoring is appropriate.</strong> More frequent bloodwork is generally recommended for FIV-positive cats. Understand what the surveillance plan is, and what signs at home should prompt earlier contact with the vet.</li>
        <li><strong>For multi-cat households, ask about realistic transmission risk.</strong> FIV transmission requires deep bite wounds — it is not spread through casual contact. Understanding the actual risk helps you make better decisions about household management.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

